< Review>
This place is my go to in the early mornings before a long day of work. I usually order via the app because times like these, it's too easy to mishear what people say. Some things get lost in the mask üò∑ which is never a problem, but not ideal when you're on the run to other places. The folks there are kind and helpful! If you frequent Peet's a lot, the app is very useful and drinks and food are made promptly with no mistakes</Review>

< text>
Unique.  I have never come out of Pete's with what I ordered. NEVER.  This time, however, I not only came out with what I ordered,  but the coffee was delightful, the foam was dry and tight, the flavor was nutty, crisp, perfectly tart, and sweet like cocoa.  The barista was courteous, concerned and pleasantly interested in what quality she has produced.  Delightful.<//text>

<Rate>2< /Rate>< Text>
I like Peet's, but there is something about this particular shop that always rubs me the wrong way. I think it is the ambient noise / sound.

In the mornings, the baristas bark out questions so loudly that it feels like an interrogation. The oldies music (think James Brown) is loud enough that people have to speak loudly to hear each other.

They need to take the sound down a notch.

Otherwise a good location and standard peets drinks.< /Text>

< text>
I'd give it 4 stars if it was a restaurant but how can you give 4 or 5 stars to a coffee shop? You would be comparing a great to top quality coffee shop to a great to top of the field restaurant and I feel that can't be done. Anyway, my reviews, my rules.

Okay, a really, really good coffee place with excellent coffee drinks, sweets, and the help. I think everyone including the patrons and the employees are pretty happy here.

One glaring thing grabs me every time I come in. I often get the cheese and apple box along with a chia latte and I feel like a criminal. Why? Because there is so much plastic involved. First the box and then all the little plastic containers with little plastic lids on them. 3 or is it 4? I feel like I've used 3 people's plastic allotment for the day each time I purchase the cheese and apple box.

For Peets Sake, if you hired one employee for let's say 3 hours a day to prepare the food on washable plates and wash the dishes after, you Peet,could save a hella amount of plastics needing to be recycled into the world system.

For Peets sake thank you Peet.<//text>

I get ant infestation sometimes in my restroom. Not only that but the other day I almost got my car towed because I did not have a permit. I was not told about needing any permits to park outside my garage when I moved in and I have been parking my car outside my apartment since I've moved in and this is the first time I've hear about the permits. When I called the office, Helena front office representative said I need the vehicle to be under my name to have a permit. I use my boyfriends vehicle, that I use to get to and from work and everyday use. I do not have proof of the vehicle under my name only his. <Gmap_id>0x80c2c626a9d4980f:0x3bb7bca5a7f43102<//Gmap_id><Review>Full of shady people and quite frankly a bit scary. I was on edge the whole time we waited there for our bus. Area outside dodgy too. We were going to walk out to Macdonalds for lunch while waiting on our bus but decided not to after seeing all the dodgy people hanging around the street (gang looking guys and homeless/drug affected).
Needs to be a staff member at the door directing people, as so many people came in confused and kept walking up and pushing in front of people at the counter to ask questions. One staff member at huge desk serving a huge line of people.
Security checkpoint isn't security. A guy in security outfit just checks your ticket and tells you which line to go to. No bag checks or security doors etc.
Many other people made me feel really uncomfortable while waiting in there.
The only reason I'm giving 2 stars is because the bus got us to where we needed to be and left on time.
The bus itself obviously isn't cleaned often  and made it an uncomfortable trip.
Whole place needs a revamp and much more staff and security presence.</Review>< Date>

<review>So I'm reviewing all of Greyhound, not just one specific location.
When I went on Greyhound's website I thought, "Wow! This looks amazing, clean, super roomy, comfy, and acommodating." Boy was I wrong.
First I'll start with the worst thing. They had no seating order/arrangement. It was pretty much first come first serve. So my husband and I got separated and couldn't sit together. Lame! Even though our tickets were numbers right next to each other.
Next, it was SO PACKED!! Like sardines! I had absolutely no leg room. The stranger next to me was bumping me and in my space the whole way. It was very awkward. The chairs were so small and very uncomfortable. I could not sleep or relax at all. It was so suppressive and tight on the bus. I just hated the whole experience.
Then we had to take our next greyhound. The first was from Sam Jose to LA. This one was LA to Vegas.
This time we were very purposeful to sit together. We arrived early. So we were standing in the front of our departing line. One of the workers came up to me and said we were not allowed to stand in line til our # was called. I was annoyed and bummed but whatever,  rules are rules. So we sat close to the area. Several times workers stated and intercoms announced passengers could not line up early or put their luggage in the lines.
Well about 30-45 minutes before departure a big family with tons of luggage AND a cooler came and stood in the line with all their stuff. Granted they just got there and there were no signs stating we couldn't stand there. So I patiently waited for a worker to tell them what they had repeatedly told all of us. No such luck. Nobody said anything. Now I was getting nervous that my hubby and I wouldn't get to sit together again. Heck no. After a few minutes more people started lining up. At the risk of us getting told to move again we got in line. Then everyone got in line, all without our # getting called. When they finally called our #, they wanted all the kids and parents to come first, under a certain age. I was panicked. Thankfully there were only a few kids. Then she told the big group with their cooler to step to the side. I was glad about that. Then we started boarding. I all but ran ahead and on to the bus and grabbed second row seats. Again the ride was bumpy, restricting, and uncomfortable but at least we were sitting together.
I think I was expecting more room and at least a seating arrangement or following your seat number on the ticket. We went with them cuz it was cheaper than flying but next time I think flying will be much more worth it.<//review>< Pictures>

< Text>
Surprisingly not nearly as sketchy as a lot of the other greyhound stations across the country. There is a little restaurant that offers okay food if you find yourself starving during a layover. Probably the freakiest thing you'll encounter here are the potheads out front and the occasional person asking to bum cigarettes or spare change. Honestly it never felt like there was anything to be concerned about. If you ever did feel bothered however there seemed to be at least one somebody doing "security". My bus was boarded promptly and left on time. No problemo.</Text>

<rate>3<//rate><text>Greyhound itself is pretty good. Good as you can expect from a bus service, anyway.

This station is okay -- nothing glamorous. Overpriced cafeteria with mediocre at best service. Smelled like weed very strongly. Again, it's a bus station. However, this bus station is in a very dodgy neighborhood. Definitely use caution when leaving the station.

I thought it was a great bus service until I started getting consecutive poor services.

1) you can either print your ticket at home or take your ticket from kiosk? It doesn't say that you can't do both. So I had my ticket in my cell phone and I thought I could print it out at the station. But no, I can't ? Imagine you had your boarding pass in your cell phone and your phone died, will the airline company not print you a ticket again in the counter ? I also had the confirmation code which I have shown and they denied to print me a new ticket. So I had to buy $7 more expensive ticket again for the same trip.

2) I arrived 20 min before the departure (2:00 pm) time of the bus. And at the last minute they get to know that the bus won't be here because the driver got sick. That's understandable and one lady said it's gonna be a 2 hour delay for that bus. Ok I waited an hour and went checking again if we are good in time. No one in the floor, not even a single person from greyhound knew anything about the 2 hours delayed bus. And at the end of two hours, I got to know there's gonna be an extra 25 min delay. This is actually their regular bus that starts at 4:25 and takes 4 hours to reach my destination. <Resp>None</Resp>< review>
Good:

1. Decent bus station. Rarity in times of vanishing public transportation in us.
2. Good collection of bending machine.
3. A couple of restaurants.
4. Washrooms we're cleaner than expected.
5. Security staff to make you feel reassured.
6. Decent WiFi @ bus station.
7. Drives are experienced and drive safely.

Bad:

1. Ticketing done through ticketing machines which can be tricky for a newbie.
2. Need more staff to help travellers.
3. More seating needed in waiting area.
5. More display boards needed.
6. There will always be someone who goes to on- bus restroom to drink.

Busses:

1. It's a hit or a miss. Newer busses can be good.
2. On the bus WiFi is a joke. Slowest public WiFi I have seen.
3. If your bus is old, something may be out of order. That includes windows, seat leaning mechanism, seat belt, power station etc.</review>

<UserId.>103037494402731713785</UserId.><username>Cailan O'Connell<//username><Time>1542300801316</Time>< rate>
1< /rate>
< Review>
Overpriced and terrible customer service. I decided to give Greyhound a chance on an LA to San Diego trip after a negative experience with their competitor, FlixBus, where the bus was several hours late. Although the tickets were more that 3x the price, I thought that would be worth it if I could depend on it to get me where I needed to go in a timely fashion.

After paying $77 for two round trip tickets, I arrived at the station to find I had been emailed the incorrect tickets. The ticketing officer was quite rude and eventually told me that if I paid $40 (cash, no receipt) to change the tickets I could call Greyhound customer support for a refund so I did that and called the support number as soon as I boarded the bus. I spent 45mins on hold with their support. Although I was sent the completely wrong tickets after double and triple checking my booking on their site (and although I was assured by the first representative of a refund), I was told by three different agents who I was transferred to that they could not help me. To top this off the bus was still 30mins late and the so called free WiFi did not work.

If this service was reliable with good customer support I would pay the extra cost of the tickets but with an experience like this I‚Äôll definitely be choosing Greyhound‚Äôs competitors in the future. If you‚Äôre not paying for dependability and support what are you paying for?< /Review>

<text>Cheap in every sense, but still worth the price. The best birdsong service for going up and down state.

There is a lot of bashing on greyhound in these comments, but it really isn't that bad. When compared with other transit methods, especially up and down the state of California, it really isn't that bad. (cheaper than a flight, more dependable than Megabus.)

Sure the staff are overworked and give poor directions to what you should do, but you will get to your destination more or less on time, especially if you book an overnight trip.

Expect especially bad service on holidays or when college students might be traveling.<//text>< Pictures>

<Review>The LA Greyhound station was not as bad as the reviews stated. They had highly trained staff who were trying to help every traveler.

The security made sure that no one bothered anyone. Free WIFI and charging docks were available though the docks were usually always crowded.

Vending machines were available for supplies for the journey.

Improvements: The loud speaker for thr announcements was not audible at all.
There was a lot of confusion on which gate to board from.
The charging docks shorted out and were not charging. The sockets were also faulty and not placed strategically.
An air freshner device can improve the ambiance.

For that reason 4/5< /Review></record>

Hey! Printers act up when you lack efficient time... But a policy that entraps the customer to loose the scheduled trip due to the policy decision to NOT print my boarding pass at the station and forces me to see my trip ruined 40 mins before departure just to charge me $20.00 extra to be on the next trip or forfeit $200.00 is a straight up, a rip off. There was No customer service. NO attentiveness to customer who wait in line as they say you will have to do, wait! Yet at their personal selection they will take a ignorant person who cuts the line and they will provide them service that they otherwise made clear to me I wouldn't receive.  Upon my reflection of the unfairness of having to wait for my turn and for her to offer this rude non-customer help as I was already committed and paid into the Greyhound company she had the audacity to remark: "sir, sir I'm on my lunch break and I'm helping this man cuz its my break and I'll choose to help him if I want!".   This was so upsetting to hear such a ignorant statement from a well established company. I won't even go into California State employment laws because I'm non drama kind a guy so I said nothing after that, i paid the toll to access my new ticket that they would print out for a trip 12 hrs after my planned departure... And sadly started to notice all the things that are quite bad about this company.

It's sad to say the reality of a rude agent can kill the excitement in traveling with such Rose colored glasses. Nothing was done with interest in my plans or satisfaction, had there been alil care in the treatment id continue to ignore that the bus does not have wifi as they advertise, that the power outlets are not providing the needed current to charge a basic smartphone, the seats are not comfortable even though they recline but worst is how most busses I've taken smell like sitting sewer from the back half... My only advised is to have no expectations in a pleasant trip and make of it what you can, once you buy your ticket ur stuck with it... No refunds no complimentary prints even though you're 40 mins before departure... No customer service no wifi no power to charge no interests in my satisfaction... Says alot about a company that otherwise boost quite the opposite.  Catch my drift?< /Review>
